On 8 June 2022 ITN announced the withdrawal of its ministers from the Government, which thereby lost its parliamentary majority, due to disagreements over spending and plans by Petkov to lift the country’s veto on initiating EU accession negotiations with North Macedonia (see 
Regional Relations
). On 22 June a motion of no confidence in the Government, proposed by GERB with the support of ITN, was supported by 123 votes in the National Assembly, prompting Petkov’s resignation. Following unsuccessful efforts to form a new administration, on 1 August President Radev signed a decree on the dissolution of the legislature, scheduling new elections for October. His social policy adviser, Galab Donev, headed a new, interim Government with effect from 2 August.

Relations with the Russian Federation improved from 1992, following the signature of co-operation agreements. In November 2012 Bulgaria signed a six-year arrangement with the Russian gas state enterprise Gazprom, which provided for a reduction in the cost of Bulgaria’s natural gas imports, together with an investment agreement on the Bulgarian section of Russia’s planned South Stream pipeline (to deliver Russian gas to southern and eastern Europe). In mid-2014, however, the Bulgarian Government suspended participation in the project, owing to an infringement procedure by the European Commission, and later that year the Russian Government confirmed it was cancelling the project. Bulgaria’s relations with Russia subsequently became strained following Russia’s annexation of Ukraine’s Crimean peninsula (see 
Other External Relations
). In January 2019 the Bulgarian Government announced that work was to commence on an additional gas pipeline, traversing Bulgaria and linking Turkey (officially redesignated as Türkiye in June 2022) with Serbia, and supplementing the TurkStream pipeline linking Russia and Turkey. The pipeline, known as Balkan Stream, entered into operation in 2021. Construction on the Bulgarian section of an EU-funded Bulgaria-Serbia Interconnector Gas Pipeline, to provide Serbia with access to Azerbaijani gas exports, began in February 2023, and the pipeline was inaugurated on 10 December.
